In article <25qqogINNo81@gap.caltech.edu> hal@cco.caltech.edu (Hal Finney) writes:
>
>Cryptographers have developed a technique called zero-knowledge proof, which
>can be used for authentication similar to what you are asking for.  The
>authentication might involve a numeric "challenge" from the vendor who wants
>to authenticate the customer, followed by a response message from the
>customer which would make use of some information that only he would have.
>The interchange is done in such a way that an eavesdropper (or the vendor
>himself) obtains NO information that would allow him to impersonate that
>customer in the future.
>
>Unfortunately, all zero-knowledge proof systems known require mathematical
>abilities which seem beyond human capability.  However, a person augmented
>with a card computer could easily do the calculations, and read off the
>results over the phone (or let his card computer's built-in modem signal
>the vendor's computer).
>
>This approach would seem to satisfy your requirements.
>

Yes indeed.  What you are describing sounds like a good compromise.
Do you have any reference to articles that I could read up on?

Alejo


